Allow "SELECT * FROM foo" emulation in pinq. Fixes #2

This is done by passing both the table and its columns
collection (before this patch only the latter was passed) to the
function that executes the 'select()' the former gets a name with
'_alias' added to it.

Then each occurrence of the target name ('foo' in 'foo for foo in
bar') is checked and if not is further restricted to one of its
attributes (so there no 'foo.zoo'), the names is changed in
'foo_alias'.

Allow coroutine macros

If a macro is a coroutine (i.e. a generator function) macro_expand()
will give the power to it about when the system has to expand its
body.

This can be useful in macros like those in tracing.py that need to
instrument the code *before* it is expanded.

Add an OptionalMatcher to the patterns module

The new matcher matches ``|`` operator and is used to match against
"or" expressions, e.g.:

(expr1 | expr2) << test

Will match expr1 or expr2
All the expressions must define the same variables.

Fix a nasty bug about symbols not available at macro execution time

Some symbols (function and modules) were imported with an ``from
macropy.core.macros *`` statement and so this bug was masked by their
untold global presence. These are necessary at macro execution time
but the user cannot really know what's needed. So I've added them as
resources that get automatically added to the user's module global
scope at import time.

It's still unclear if some of them will/can pose some issues when
using exported code.

Improve macro load performance

Improve macro load time.

We have a large code base, and macropy caused the import time of our project
to go to about 3s on most people's laptops. These changes, which reduce
AST walking, reduced it to about 1.6s.
